EIS was used to monitor the changes of interfacial properties at different electrode surfaces in the presence of 10 mmol L−1 [Fe(CN)6]3-/4-(0.1 mol L−1 KCl) (Fig. 3B). The inset simulated the circuit diagram, including the resistance of the electrolyte solution (R

                           s
                        ), the resistance of charge transfer (R

                           ct
                        ), Warburg impedance (W), and the capacity of the double layer (C). The electron transfer resistance (Ret) value of the bare gold electrode was 268 Ω (line a), indicating a fast charge-transfer process. After the immobilization of the peptide-NGQDs-Ru@SiO2 nanoprobe, the Ret value dropped to 81.8 Ω (line b), this was due to the fact that NGQDs-Ru@SiO2 in the ECL nanoprobe was beneficial to electron conduction. The Ret increased after MCH filled the empty spots (line c, 771 Ω), because a barrier to the interfacial electron transfer of MCH was established. Finally, when MMP-2 was further self-assembled in the ECL nanoprobe, a further increase in Ret to 1046 Ω was found. This increase was ascribed to the fact that MMP-2 cleaved the peptide, leading to the moving away of a part of the peptide-based NGQDs-Ru@SiO2 from the surface of the electrode. These EIS responses corresponded to the CV conclusions, which further demonstrated the successful manufacturing of the self-enhanced ECL nanocomposites-labeled peptide biosensor.

Under optimal conditions, the ECL intensities at different concentrations of MMP-2 on the proposed biosensor were measured. Fig. 4
                        A presented that the ECL signal gradually reduced with increasing MMP-2 concentration. By measuring the decreased ECL signal, the proposed peptide-NGQDs-Ru@SiO2 biosensor for MMP-2 exhibited a linear regression in the range of 0.01–185 ng mL−1 with a detection limit of 6.5 pg mL−1 (S/N = 3). The equation was ΔI = 23.57C + 2116.1 (unit of C is ng mL−1). The correlation coefficient was 0.9901. We compared the proposed biosensor in this work with some previously reported biosensors (Table 1
                        ). The linear range was wider than those of the fluorescence method [7,9]. Although the test performance was not as superior as the reported electrochemical approach [10–12], the peptide-NGQDs-Ru@SiO2 biosensor had a lower detection limit (6.5 pg mL−1) than those reported for the ECL biosensor [14,15]. This finding was due to the fact that the NGQDs-Ru@SiO2 could amplify the signal and exhibit excellent combination property.
